  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses 5% growth and 8.5% discount rate. But reasonable people disagree on these numbers. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions. Find the combination you believe in.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Because LMT is a mature, slower-growing company, its valuation is highly sensitive to the discount rate and the terminal growth assumptions.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Increased defense spending:</strong> Geopolitical tensions could lead to sustained, higher-than-expected increases in the US defense budget and foreign military sales.</li>
    <li><strong>Share buybacks:</strong> Lockheed Martin consistently repurchases shares. Fewer shares = higher per-share value over time. Our model uses a static share count.</li>
    <li><strong>Margin expansion:</strong> If LMT can improve efficiency or secure more favorable contract terms, a small increase in margin on $75B+ in revenue translates to massive FCF gains.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Budget cuts:</strong> The US government is the primary customer. Fiscal austerity or shifts in defense priorities could significantly impact revenue.</li>
    <li><strong>Program execution issues:</strong> Delays, cost overruns, or technical problems on major programs (like the F-35) can result in delayed payments and reduced profitability.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt burden:</strong> With over $21B in debt, a rising interest rate environment could increase interest expenses and reduce cash available to shareholders over the long term.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, then lets math determine the price. It's the only valuation method that directly connects cash flow generation to value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why an 8.5% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents your required return. For a defense prime contractor with highly visible revenue streams and virtually zero risk of obsolescence, the risk profile is lower than the broader market. 8.5% provides a reasonable premium over the 10-year Treasury yield.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the Net Cash negative?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Lockheed Martin carries significantly more debt ($21.7B) than cash and short-term investments ($4.1B). This negative net cash position directly reduces the Equity Value in our calculation, demonstrating the impact of leverage on valuation.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

